 Articles and further documents published under an Open scientific paper
public License are protected by copyright. Anyone may access, download,
copy, translate, text and data mine (but may not redistribute, display
or adapt) the articles and documents for non-commercial purposes
provided that users:

1.  Cite the article using an appropriate bibliographic citation
    (i.e. author(s), journal or source, article title, volume,
     issue, page numbers, DOI and the link to the definitive 
     published version on github)
    
    The along with the citation there should be information about 
    the latest technical git commit identifier for the given document
    in the time of "usage". The time of "usage" is defined by the
    latest date and time among the followings:

     * The publication time of the content in which the document(s)
       contents were used as a source.

     * Time of incorporating the citation in the contents where the
       document(s) contents were used as a source

2.  Maintain the integrity of the article(s)

3.  Retain copyright notices and links to these terms and conditions
    so it is clear to other users what can and cannot be done with the article.

4.  Ensure that, for any content in the article that is identified as belonging
    to a third party, any re-use complies with the copyright policies of 
    that third party.

5.  Any translations, for which a prior translation agreement with the author
    has not been established, must prominently display the statement:
    "This is an unofficial translation of an article that appeared in an 
    Open scientific paper public Licence publication found at <source>.
    The author has not endorsed this translation."
    Where <source> is a placeholder to add an extended bibliographic citation,
    as above which needs to be filled for referring the translated document(s).

